### Topics

*   See also: [Outline of discrete mathematics](/Outline_of_discrete_mathematics)

#### Theoretical Computer Science

*   Main article: [Theoretical computer science](/Theoretical_computer_science)

[Complexity](/Computational_complexity_theory) studies how long [algorithms](/Algorithm) take. Like this [sorting routine](/Quicksort). It’s a race against time, or against futility.
[Computational geometry](/Computational_geometry) takes [algorithms](/Algorithm) and applies them to shapes. Because the real world isn't just abstract lines.

Theoretical computer science is where discrete mathematics gets its hands dirty with computing. It leans heavily on [graph theory](/Graph_theory) and [mathematical logic](/Mathematical_logic). Algorithms and data structures are central. [Computability](/Computability) asks what can be computed, period. Complexity measures the cost – time, space, sanity. [Automata theory](/Automata_theory) and [formal language](/Formal_language) theory are close cousins. [Petri nets](/Petri_net) and [process algebras](/Process_algebra) try to model systems. We even analyze [VLSI](/VLSI) circuits with these tools. [Computational geometry](/Computational_geometry) applies algorithms to shapes, and [computer image analysis](/Computer_image_analysis) to pixels. It even dabbles in continuous computational topics, just to keep things interesting.

#### Information Theory

*   Main article: [Information theory](/Information_theory)

The [ASCII](/ASCII) codes for "Wikipedia" in [binary](/Binary_numeral_system). A way to represent information, and a foundation for [information theory](/Information_theory) and [algorithms](/Algorithm).

Information theory quantifies information. [Coding theory](/Coding_theory) designs methods for reliable data transmission and storage. It also has its continuous side, with [analog signals](/Analog_signal), [analog coding](/Analog_coding), and [analog encryption](/Analog_encryption).

#### Logic

*   Main article: [Mathematical logic](/Mathematical_logic)

Logic is the study of valid reasoning. And the proof that your reasoning is, in fact, invalid. It examines [consistency](/Consistency), [soundness](/Soundness), and [completeness](/Completeness_(logic)). Take [Peirce's law](/Peirce%27s_law) – a theorem in most logics, verifiable with a [truth table](/Truth_table). The study of [mathematical proof](/Mathematical_proof) is crucial, leading to [automated theorem proving](/Automated_theorem_proving) and [formal verification](/Formal_verification) of software.

[Logical formulas](/Well-formed_formula) are discrete. [Proofs](/Proof_theory) are discrete too, forming finite [trees](/Tree_structure)&#160;[10] or [directed acyclic graphs](/Directed_acyclic_graph).&#160;[11]&#160;[12]&#160;Each [inference step](/Rule_of_inference) combines [premises](/Premise) to yield a conclusion. [Truth values](/Truth_value) are usually binary – true or false – but [fuzzy logic](/Fuzzy_logic) exists. And then there are the infinite proof trees of [infinitary logic](/Infinitary_logic).&#160;[13]&#160;

#### Set Theory

*   Main article: [Set theory](/Set_theory)

Set theory studies [sets](/Set_(mathematics)) – collections of things. Like {blue, white, red}, or the infinite set of [prime numbers](/Prime_number). [Partially ordered sets](/Partially_ordered_set) and other [relations](/Relation_(mathematics)) pop up everywhere.

In discrete math, we focus on [countable sets](/Countable_set), including [finite sets](/Finite_set). The real fireworks of set theory, dealing with different kinds of [infinite sets](/Infinite_set), initiated by [Georg Cantor](/Georg_Cantor), are generally outside the scope of discrete mathematics. [Descriptive set theory](/Descriptive_set_theory), for instance, relies heavily on continuous mathematics.

#### Combinatorics

*   Main article: [Combinatorics](/Combinatorics)

Combinatorics is about how discrete structures can be combined or arranged.
[Enumerative combinatorics](/Enumerative_combinatorics) counts things. The [twelvefold way](/Twelvefold_way) is a unified framework for counting [permutations](/Permutations), [combinations](/Combinations), and [partitions](/Partition_of_a_set).
[Analytic combinatorics](/Analytic_combinatorics) uses [complex analysis](/Complex_analysis) and [probability theory](/Probability_theory) to count. It aims for [asymptotic formulae](/Asymptotic_analysis), unlike enumerative combinatorics with its explicit formulas and [generating functions](/Generating_functions).
[Topological combinatorics](/Topological_combinatorics) brings [topology](/Topology) and [algebraic topology](/Algebraic_topology)/[combinatorial topology](/Combinatorial_topology) into the mix.
Design theory studies [combinatorial designs](/Combinatorial_design) – collections of subsets with specific [intersection](/Set_intersection) properties.
[Partition theory](/Partition_theory) deals with [integer partitions](/Integer_partition), and is closely linked to [q-series](/Q-series), [special functions](/Special_functions), and [orthogonal polynomials](/Orthogonal_polynomials). Once part of [number theory](/Number_theory) and [analysis](/Analysis), it's now its own thing.
[Order theory](/Order_theory) studies [partially ordered sets](/Partially_ordered_sets), both finite and infinite.

#### Graph Theory

*   Main article: [Graph theory](/Graph_theory)

[Graph theory](/Graph_theory) has ties to [group theory](/Group_theory). This [truncated tetrahedron](/Truncated_tetrahedron) graph is connected to the [alternating group](/Alternating_group) A₄.

Graph theory, the study of [graphs](/Graph_(discrete_mathematics)) and [networks](/Network_theory), is often bundled with combinatorics, but it’s grown too substantial to be just a subfield.&#160;[14]&#160;Graphs are fundamental to discrete math. They model everything from social networks to communication systems. In computer science, they represent networks, data organization, and computation flow. In pure math, they connect to geometry and [topology](/Topology), like [knot theory](/Knot_theory). [Algebraic graph theory](/Algebraic_graph_theory) links with group theory, and [topological graph theory](/Topological_graph_theory) with topology. There are even [continuous graphs](/Continuous_graph), but most research remains firmly in the discrete camp.

#### Number Theory

The [Ulam spiral](/Ulam_spiral) shows [prime numbers](/Prime_number) in black, hinting at patterns in their [distribution](/Prime_number).

*   Main article: [Number theory](/Number_theory)

Number theory investigates the properties of numbers, especially [integers](/Integer). It's crucial for [cryptography](/Cryptography) and [cryptanalysis], particularly [modular arithmetic](/Modular_arithmetic), [diophantine equations](/Diophantine_equations), congruences, primes, and [primality testing](/Primality_test). Other discrete aspects include the [geometry of numbers](/Geometry_of_numbers). [Analytic number theory](/Analytic_number_theory) borrows from continuous methods. Topics like [transcendental numbers](/Transcendental_number), [diophantine approximation](/Diophantine_approximation), [p-adic analysis](/P-adic_analysis), and [function fields](/Function_field_of_an_algebraic_variety) venture beyond the purely discrete.

#### Algebraic Structures

*   Main article: [Abstract algebra](/Abstract_algebra)

[Algebraic structures](/Algebraic_structure) can be discrete or continuous. Discrete examples include: [Boolean algebra](/Boolean_algebra_(logic)) for [logic gates](/Logic_gate) and programming; [relational algebra](/Relational_algebra) for [databases](/Databases); discrete and finite [groups](/Group_(mathematics)), [rings](/Ring_(mathematics)), and [fields](/Field_(mathematics)) vital for [algebraic coding theory](/Algebraic_coding_theory); discrete [semigroups](/Semigroup) and [monoids](/Monoid) in [formal languages](/Formal_languages).

#### Discrete Analogues of Continuous Mathematics

Many concepts from continuous mathematics have discrete counterparts: [discrete calculus](/Discrete_calculus), [discrete Fourier transforms](/Discrete_Fourier_transform), [discrete geometry](/Discrete_geometry), [discrete logarithms](/Discrete_logarithm), [discrete differential geometry](/Discrete_differential_geometry), [discrete exterior calculus](/Discrete_exterior_calculus), [discrete Morse theory](/Discrete_Morse_theory), [discrete optimization](/Discrete_optimization), [discrete probability theory](/Discrete_probability_theory), [discrete probability distribution](/Discrete_probability_distribution), [difference equations](/Difference_equation), [discrete dynamical systems](/Discrete_dynamical_system), and [discrete vector measures](/Shapley%E2%80%93Folkman_lemma).

##### Calculus of Finite Differences, Discrete Analysis, and Discrete Calculus

In [discrete calculus](/Discrete_calculus) and the [calculus of finite differences](/Calculus_of_finite_differences), a [function](/Function_(mathematics)) on [integers](/Integer) is a [sequence](/Sequence). These can be finite, from data, or infinite, from a [discrete dynamical system](/Discrete_dynamical_system). They can be defined explicitly, by a formula, or implicitly by a [recurrence relation](/Recurrence_relation) or [difference equation](/Difference_equation). Difference equations mimic [differential equations](/Differential_equation) by using differences instead of derivatives. They can approximate differential equations or stand on their own. Many questions about differential equations have counterparts for difference equations. Just as [integral transforms](/Integral_transforms) study continuous functions, [discrete transforms](/Discrete_transform) handle discrete functions. Beyond [discrete metric spaces](/Discrete_metric_space), there are [discrete topological spaces](/Discrete_topological_space), [finite metric spaces](/Finite_metric_space), and [finite topological spaces](/Finite_topological_space).

The [time scale calculus](/Time_scale_calculus) unifies the theory of [difference equations](/Difference_equations) and [differential equations](/Differential_equations), useful for modeling mixed discrete and continuous data. [Hybrid dynamical systems](/Hybrid_system) offer another approach.

##### Discrete Geometry

[Discrete geometry](/Discrete_geometry) and combinatorial geometry examine the combinatorial properties of discrete geometric objects. [Tiling of the plane](/Tessellation) is a classic problem.

In [algebraic geometry](/Algebraic_geometry), curves can be extended to discrete settings using the [spectra](/Spectrum_of_a_ring) of [polynomial rings](/Polynomial_ring) over [finite fields](/Finite_field) as models of [affine spaces](/Affine_space). [Subvarieties](/Algebraic_variety) then become the curves. These spaces have finite points, but the curves are analogues of their continuous counterparts. For instance, a point like $V(x-c) \subset \operatorname{Spec} K[x] = \mathbb{A}^1$ can be seen as $\operatorname{Spec} K[x]/(x-c) \cong \operatorname{Spec} K$ (a point) or as the spectrum $\operatorname{Spec} K[x]_{(x-c)}$ of the [local ring at (x-c)](/Localization_of_a_ring), which is a point with its neighborhood. Algebraic varieties have [Zariski tangent spaces](/Zariski_tangent_space), allowing calculus-like features.

##### Discrete Modelling

In [applied mathematics](/Applied_mathematics), [discrete modelling](/Discrete_modelling) is the discrete version of [continuous modelling](/Continuous_modelling). Discrete formulas are fit to [data](/Data), often using [recurrence relations](/Recurrence_relation). [Discretization](/Discretization) is the process of transforming continuous models into discrete ones, usually for simpler calculation through approximation. [Numerical analysis](/Numerical_analysis) is a prime example.

