### Challenges

The history of discrete mathematics is marked by difficult problems that have shaped the field. In [graph theory](/Graph_theory), the pursuit of proving the [four color theorem](/Four_color_theorem) – that any map can be colored with four colors such that no adjacent regions share the same color – spurred much research. [Kenneth Appel](/Kenneth_Appel) and [Wolfgang Haken](/Wolfgang_Haken) finally proved it in 1976, with significant computer assistance.&#160;[15]&#160;

In [logic](/Mathematical_logic), [David Hilbert](/David_Hilbert)'s second problem from 1900 asked for a proof of the [consistency](/Consistent) of the [axioms](/Axioms) of [arithmetic](/Arithmetic). [Gödel's second incompleteness theorem](/G%C3%B6del%27s_second_incompleteness_theorem), proven in 1931, demonstrated this was impossible within arithmetic itself. Hilbert's tenth problem, determining if a polynomial [Diophantine equation](/Diophantine_equation) has integer solutions, was resolved by [Yuri Matiyasevich](/Yuri_Matiyasevich) in 1970, showing it could not be done universally.&#160;[Matiyasevich's theorem](/Matiyasevich%27s_theorem)&#160;

The need to [break](/Cryptanalysis) German codes during [World War II](/World_War_II) accelerated progress in [cryptography](/Cryptography) and [theoretical computer science](/Theoretical_computer_science). The [first programmable digital electronic computer](/Colossus_computer), developed at [Bletchley Park](/Bletchley_Park) under the guidance of [Alan Turing](/Alan_Turing) and his work on [On Computable Numbers](/On_Computable_Numbers), was a direct result.&#160;[16]&#160;The [Cold War](/Cold_War) ensured cryptography remained vital, leading to breakthroughs like [public-key cryptography](/Public-key_cryptography). The [telecommunications industry](/Telecommunications_industry) also drove advances in graph theory and [information theory](/Information_theory). The demand for [formal verification](/Formal_verification) in [software development](/Software_development) for [safety-critical systems](/Safety-critical_system) fueled progress in [automated theorem proving](/Automated_theorem_proving).

[Computational geometry](/Computational_geometry) became integral to [computer graphics](/Computer_graphics_(computer_science)) in modern [video games](/Video_game) and [computer-aided design](/Computer-aided_design) tools.

Fields like theoretical computer science, graph theory, and [combinatorics](/Combinatorics) are essential for tackling the complex [bioinformatics](/Bioinformatics) challenges of understanding the [tree of life](/Phylogenetic_tree).&#160;[17]&#160;

Currently, one of the most notorious open problems in theoretical computer science is the [P = NP problem](/P_%3D_NP_problem), concerning the relationship between [complexity classes](/Complexity_class) [P](/P_(complexity)) and [NP](/NP_(complexity)). The [Clay Mathematics Institute](/Clay_Mathematics_Institute) has offered a $1 million [USD](/USD) prize for its solution, alongside prizes for six other mathematical challenges.&#160;[18]&#160;

